body:
I like the idea, although I'm not sure this is that useful, to be honest. It reminds me a lot of `-PipelineVariable`, and I don't see a lot of folks really using that, either. It's a fairly complex thing to reason through and understand, iterating multiple pipelines at once.

Essentially what this would end up doing is conceptually and functionally similar to this (though, if it could be done as you describe, we'd want there to be less overhead involved).

```powershell
function next($enumerator) {
    if ($enumerator.MoveNext()) {
        $enumerator.Current
    }
}

$a = (1..1e9).GetEnumerator()

1..100 | ForEach-Object {
    Write-Host "Pipeline: $_"
    Write-Host "`$a item: $(next $a)"
}
```

I'm also not really sure that deferring the processing is going to be that valuable. For example, in your last example with $b, it's not possible to really defer the creation of the whole array without completely re-architecting how the `..` operator itself works. As soon as that script gets processed for the first time, the array has to be created in full, and then the enumerator captured so the later parts of the script can enumerate it.

Overall it's an interesting idea, but I'm concerned that it would be overly complex both to actually make use of as well as just to implement it. I think PowerShell's array creation and general pipeline semantics would need a bit of a rethink to make this a worthwhile thing to implement.

Something like this is possible, and is probably the closest we can feasibly get:

<details>

<summary>PipelineEnumerable.cs</summary>

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections;
using System.Management.Automation;

namespace Example
{
    public class PipelineEnumerable : IEnumerable
    {
        private readonly ScriptBlock _scriptBlock;

        private readonly IEnumerable _input;

        public PipelineEnumerable(ScriptBlock scriptBlock)
        {
            _scriptBlock = scriptBlock;
        }

        public PipelineEnumerable(ScriptBlock scriptBlock, IEnumerable input) {
            _scriptBlock = scriptBlock;
            _input = input;
        }

        public IEnumerator GetEnumerator()
        {
            return new PipelineEnumerator(
                _scriptBlock.GetSteppablePipeline(CommandOrigin.Runspace),
                _input?.GetEnumerator());
        }
    }

    public class PipelineEnumerator : IEnumerator, IDisposable
    {
        private readonly SteppablePipeline _pipe;

        private readonly IEnumerator _input;

        private IEnumerator _output;

        private bool _beginWasInvoked;

        private bool _processWasInvoked;

        private bool _endWasInvoked;

        private bool _isDisposed;

        public PipelineEnumerator(SteppablePipeline pipe, IEnumerator input)
        {
            _pipe = pipe;
            _input = input;
        }

        public object Current => _output.Current;

        public bool MoveNext()
        {
            if (!_beginWasInvoked)
            {
                bool expectingInput = _input is not null;
                _pipe.Begin(expectingInput);
                _beginWasInvoked = true;
                // Always forget `SteppablePipeline.Begin` has a void return for some reason.
                // if (($this.out = ($res)?.GetEnumerator())?.MoveNext()) {
                //     return $true
                // }
            }

            if (_output?.MoveNext() is true)
            {
                return true;
            }

            while (_input?.MoveNext() is true)
            {
                Array res = _pipe.Process(_input.Current);
                _processWasInvoked = true;
                if ((_output = res?.GetEnumerator())?.MoveNext() is true)
                {
                    return true;
                }
            }

            if (!_processWasInvoked)
            {
                Array res = _pipe.Process();
                _processWasInvoked = true;
                if ((_output = res?.GetEnumerator())?.MoveNext() is true)
                {
                    return true;
                }
            }

            if (!_endWasInvoked)
            {
                Array res = _pipe.End();
                _endWasInvoked = true;
                if ((_output = res?.GetEnumerator())?.MoveNext() is true)
                {
                    return true;
                }
            }

            return false;
        }

        public void Reset() => throw new NotSupportedException();

        protected virtual void Dispose(bool disposing)
        {
            if (_isDisposed)
            {
                return;
            }

            if (disposing)
            {
                _pipe.Dispose();
            }

            _isDisposed = true;
        }

        public void Dispose()
        {
            Dispose(disposing: true);
            GC.SuppressFinalize(this);
        }
    }
}
```

</details>

(side note, try implementing the above in a PowerShell class and you get some *real* weird errors)

This sort of highlights the problem with the idea though.  There isn't a way to defer execution after a single pipeline object has been emitted.

For example, if you were to do this:

```powershell
$b = [Example.PipelineEnumerable]::new{
	ForEach-Object {
		foreach ($a in 0..3) {
			$a
			$host.UI.WriteErrorLine('ehhh')
		}
	}
}

$e = $b.GetEnumerator()
$e.MoveNext()
$e.Current
```

You get

```raw
ehhh
ehhh
ehhh
ehhh
True
0
```

During a pipeline this works because when one item is emitted to the pipeline, execution moves immediately to the next pipeline element's process block.  Without an immediate next method to call, you **must** finish the block. There is no way to suspend and resume execution of a method in dotnet.  Even when C# *seems* to do this (e.g. with async/await and `yield return`), the compiler is really completely changing the method to enable this.

Great stuff, @SeeminglyScience; thanks for clarifying the limitations of steppable pipelines outside of actual pipelines.

I played around with parallel thread jobs as a - suboptimal - alternative: the `ForEach-CorrespondingObject` function defined below uses _queues_ to buffer output objects in order to ensure that only corresponding output objects are processed; with large output sets and widely differing output timing among the input script blocks, however, you may still run out of memory.

Of course, this approach isn't efficient, because buffering happens both in the thread jobs and in the function, and output is periodically collected with a short sleep interval between tries.

Here's a sample call and its output, with verbose output enabled:

* Two infinite producer script blocks are supplied, which simply output as sequence of numbers, and a the processing script block simple echoes the corresponding number pairs.
  * One of the blocks periodically cleans the screen, to avoid memory issues from overly long console scrollback buffers.
  
* Note that the producers do not run in a _tight_ loop - they sleep briefly between outputting numbers - as there is currently no batching mechanism for `Receive-Object` calls, which could cause a given call to receive objects indefinitely; see:
   * #15234 - the inability to retrieve a given number of objects from a job in a consuming manner.
   * #5433. - proposal to call `Receive-Object` with a timeout.

```powershell
{ 
  $i=0; $sleepMs = 10
  while ($true) { 
    (++$i); Start-Sleep -ms $sleepMs
  } 
}, 
{ 
  $i=0; $sleepMs = 10
  while ($true) { 
    (++$i); Start-Sleep -ms $sleepMs
    # To avoid memory problems with an overly long scrollback buffer, we clear it
    # periodically.
  if ($i -gt 1000 -and $i % 1000 -eq 1) { (-not $IsWindows -or [bool] $env:WT_SESSION) ? [Console]::Write("`e[2J`e[3J`e[H") : [Console]::Clear(); [Console]::WriteLine('(Screen cleared.)') } 
  } 
} | ForEach-CorrespondingObject { '{0} - {1}' -f $_[0], $_[1] } -Verbose
```

Sample output:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/588825/114780602-a0bd5900-9d45-11eb-94e8-b2344d6bd22c.png)


<details>
<summary><pre>ForEach-CorrespondingObject</pre> source code.</summary>

```powershell
# Sample call.
function ForEach-CorrespondingObject {
  [CmdletBinding(PositionalBinding = $false)]
  param(
    [Parameter(Mandatory, Position = 0)]
    [scriptblock] $Process
    ,
    [Parameter(Mandatory, ValueFromPipeline)]
    [scriptblock] $InputScriptBlock
  )
  begin {
    $allInputScriptBlocks = [System.Collections.Generic.List[scriptblock]]::new()
  }
  process {
    $allInputScriptBlocks.Add($InputScriptBlock)
  }
  end {
    # Start a thread job for each script block.
    Write-Verbose "Launching $($allInputScriptBlocks.Count) jobs..."
    [array] $jobs = foreach ($sb in $allInputScriptBlocks) {
      Start-ThreadJob -ThrottleLimit $allInputScriptBlocks.Count $sb
    }
    try {
      # Initialize an array of output queues parallelling the jobs and
      # temporarily storing their output objects.
      $outputQueues = [Collections.Queue[]]::new($jobs.Count)
      for ($i = 0; $i -lt $outputQueues.Count; ++$i) { $outputQueues[$i] = [Collections.Queue]::new() }
      # Start collecting output.
      do {
        Write-Verbose "(Re)entering output-collection loop..."
        # Sleep a little between attempts to collect output.
        Start-Sleep -ms 50
        # Collect currently available output.
        for ($i = 0; $i -lt $jobs.Count; ++$i) {
          $job = $jobs[$i]
          if (-not $job) {
            # Set a completed job's output queue to $null, if it is now empty.
            if ($outputQueues[$i] -and $outputQueues[$i].Count -eq 0) { $outputQueues[$i] = $null }
          }
          else {
            $done = $job.State -in 'Completed', 'Failed'
            if ($job.HasMoreData) {
              Write-Verbose "Receiving from job #$i..."
              # Note: using Select-Object -First <n> is unfortunately NOT an option: see https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell/issues/15234
              # With a tight loop as input, this can end up collecting a lot of data.
              Receive-Job -Job $job | ForEach-Object {
                $outputQueues[$i].Enqueue($_)
              }
            }
            else {
              Write-Verbose "Job #$i has no data."
            }
            if (-not $job.HasMoreData -and $done) {
              $jobs[$i] = $null; Remove-Job $job
            }
          }
        }
    
        # Process all corresponding objects currently in the queues.
        if ($activeQueues = $outputQueues -ne $null) {
          $availableOutputSetsCount = [Linq.Enumerable]::Min([int[]] $activeQueues.ForEach('Count'))
          Write-Verbose "Processing $($availableOutputSetsCount) available output set(s)..."
          for ($i = 0; $i -lt $availableOutputSetsCount; ++$i) {
            [array] $outputSet = foreach ($queue in $outputQueues) { $queue -and $queue.Count ? $queue.Dequeue() : $null }
            # Pass each set of corresponding output objects to the -Process script block.
            ForEach-Object -InputObject $outputSet -Process $Process
          }
        }
      } while ($jobs -ne $null -or $activeQueues)
    }
    finally {
      if ($activeJobs = $jobs -ne $null) {
        Remove-Job -Job $activeJobs -Force
      }
    }
  }
}
```

